<div class="container">
  <div class="row m-3">

    <div class="col">
      <h1>API</h1>

      <hr>

      <p>
      The data in this application can also be accessed in JSON format with direct requests to an API.
      Use the following URL to access all (public) dates.
      </p>

      <pre>
<code><%= request.original_url %>/v1/data</code>
      </pre>

      <p>
      You can also filter the data with this interface to only access the subsets relevant for you.
      With the following URL you get - for example - only one date with the Lab Number <b>AAR-1847</b>.
      </p>

      <pre>
<code><%= request.original_url %>/v1/data<b>?query_labnr=AAR-1847</b></code>
      </pre>

      <p>
      The <b>|</b> ("pipe") operator allows you to combine multiple filter keys. <b>|</b> represents a
      logical <b>OR</b>. That means the following URL will give you both dates <b>AAR-1847</b> and <b>KN-2506</b>.
      </p>

      <pre>
<code><%= request.original_url %>/v1/data<b>?query_labnr=AAR-1847|KN-2506</b></code>
      </pre>

      <p>
      You can also combine multiple filter criteria by adding filter parameters to the URL with the
      <b>&</b> ("and") operator. The parameters are combined with a logical <b>AND</b>.
      The following query will therefore give you all dates measured on charcoal from Germany.
      </p>

      <pre>
<code><%= request.original_url %>/v1/data<b>?query_country=Germany&query_material=charcoal</b></code>
      </pre>

      <p>
      Heres a <b>list of the available filter criteria</b>:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>query_labnr</li>
        <li>query_site</li>
        <li>query_site_type</li>
        <li>query_country</li>
        <li>query_feature</li>
        <li>query_material</li>
        <li>query_species</li>
      </ul>

      <hr>

      <h2>Usage expectations</h2>

      <p>
        XRONOS is an open resource, and we welcome responsible reuse of its data.
        When accessing the API or harvesting pages programmatically, please follow
        basic principles of polite web access: identify yourself, respect the site
        policy, make requests slowly, and avoid asking for the same resource repeatedly.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          Set an informative <code>User-Agent</code> string that identifies your
          project or application and provides a contact email or URL.
        </li>
        <li>
          Respect <code>robots.txt</code> and avoid crawling paths that are excluded
          there.
        </li>
        <li>
          Avoid unnecessary repeated requests. Cache responses locally where possible.
        </li>
        <li>
          Keep request rates moderate and avoid parallel scraping or deep pagination
          loops.
        </li>
        <li>
          Prefer documented API endpoints or flat-file data exports over scraping
          HTML pages.
        </li>
        <li>
          If you need a substantial part of the database, use the data dump or contact
          us before starting large-scale automated harvesting.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        These expectations follow the general principles of
        <a href="https://dmi3kno.github.io/polite/">polite web access</a>.
        Automated traffic that causes excessive load or does not identify itself may
        be rate-limited or blocked.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>



